



Q1. Classical Arabic Secondry Phonemes?
As noted by Bloomfield (1933), Secondry Phonemes are not part of any simple (e.g. alphabet compsing a syllables) meaningful
speech-form taken by itself, but appear only when two or more are combined into a larger form, or else when speech-forms
are used in certain ways-- especially as sentences. In English foot Σ, syllable σ stress functions as a secondry phoneme 
where the first syllable in nouns recieves the primary stress while it is the second syllable for a "verb", hence /'ob,ject/ and /ob'ject/ respectively.

الضاربَ الشاتمَ المكرِمَ المعطيَة درهما القائمُ في داره أخوكَ سوطاً أكرمَ الأكلُ طعامهَ غلامُه زيدٌ عمرو خالدٍ بكراً عبدَالله أخوكْ.
