												><كلامنا لفظٌ مفيد كـــــاســـــتــــقــــــــمِ <> إسم وفعل ثم حرف الكلم>< 


In order to recognize the distinctive features of "forms" in our language,
we need only to determine which features of sound are "different".  
Linguistic features are divided onto: acoustic & phonemic.
The features of sound in any utterance (As described by the 
Arabists' nomenclature) are the Gross Acoustic Features (GAF) of the 
Utterance in question. The GAF are either indifferent features
(non-distinctive i.e. not connected to the meaning and essential to
the communication), or distinctive. Stead of Bloomfield’
assumption, that the difference between distinctive and non-distinctive
features lies entirely in the habit of the speaker, we adopt the strict 
Arabists' nomenclature classification of the GAF. The GAF significance 
lies in forms parsing. Where approporiate, we shall adopt
Chomsky's SPE notation and rules. 
This represents our record of the system of written symbols
which provides one sign for each phoneme of Arabic language [char]
i.e. phonetic alphabet. Phonetic transcription /char/ is our record of
the shape of these symbols in an act of speech. 












Rules  describing how underlying representations (URs) are transformed into surface forms (phonetic representations). These rules use distinctive features and apply in a derivational manner. A list of phonological rules are given with formal notation:

1. Assimilation Rule.

A phoneme changes to share features with a neighboring sound.

Notation:
￼
(where ￼ is a distinctive feature, ￼ and ￼ represent different values, and ￼ and ￼ are the phonological contexts.)

Example:
	•	English nasal assimilation:
￼
(e.g., “input” → [ɪnpʊt] vs. “impossible” → [ɪmpɑsəbl])

2. Dissimilation Rule

A sound changes to become less similar to a neighboring sound.

Notation:
￼

Example:
	•	Latin arbore → arbol (where */r/ changes to */l/ to avoid two “r” sounds in the word).

3. Insertion (Epenthesis) Rule

A phoneme is inserted into a word.

Notation:
\[
\varnothing \rightarrow X / A \_ B
\]
(where \( \varnothing \) represents an empty slot, meaning the sound is inserted.)

Example:
	•	English plural epenthesis:
\[
\varnothing \rightarrow [ə] / sibilant \_ z
\]
(e.g., “bus” → [bʌsəz] in plural form)

4. Deletion (Elision) Rule

A phoneme is deleted in certain contexts.

Notation:
\[
X \rightarrow \varnothing / A \_ B
\]

Example:
	•	English h-deletion in unstressed syllables:
\[
h \rightarrow \varnothing / \_ unstressed vowel
\]
(e.g., “he” → [i] in casual speech)

5. Metathesis Rule

Two adjacent phonemes switch positions.

Notation:
￼

Example:
	•	English ask → [æks] (in some dialects).

6. Vowel Reduction Rule

Unstressed vowels are reduced to a schwa /ə/.

Notation:
￼

Example:
	•	“Canada” → [ˈkænədə] (with reduced final vowel).

7. Flapping Rule (in American English)

A /t/ or /d/ becomes a flap [ɾ] between vowels.

Notation:
￼

Example:
	•	“butter” → [ˈbʌɾɚ]


